  <a name="planning"></a>
  <h1>
    Planning
  </h1>
  <p>
    <strong>Establishing Rituals</strong> played a significant
    role in the success of this project.
    With a gap in solution quality, I kicked off several
    rituals to empower feedback, collaboration, innovation,
    alignment, and big picture thinking.
    This was an ongoing practice.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-focus">
    <header class="case-study-focus__header">
      <h3>
        Rituals
      </h3>
    </header>

    <ul>
      <li>
        Bi-weekly Design critiques for feedback and quality.
      </li>
      <li>
        Weekly Design studio time for cross-functional collaboration.
      </li>
      <li>
        Weekly Design calibration for design quality calibration.
      </li>
      <li>
        Quarterly vision sprints for cross-functional future thinking.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    In addition, I leveled-up the design function's ability
    <strong>to leverage data and research</strong>
    to inform design decisions.
    I took 2 steps to address this.
    The first step was to
    help designers build a relationship with data.
    I did so by making a specific ask;
    pair with a Data Scientist between projects
    and work together to come up with a list of assumptions.
    The second step was to build more design rigor into
    our A/B testing processes.
    In critiques and 1:1s I would
    focus on the simple things like isolating design
    variables and designing with intent to learn.
  </p>

  <p>
    Finally, to bring divergent ideas, creativity, and engagement to the
    project, I pitched an <strong>inclusive planning process.</strong>
    Working with my cross-functional leads partners, we combined a tops down,
    bottoms up, approach that would allow everyone to contribute. We landed on
    the “W” approach. Leads would establish a foundational direction from
    existing information, contributions and feedback came from squads, and back
    up and down until we had a high level plan for the year.
  </p>

  <a name="designing"></a>
  <h1>
    Designing
  </h1>

  <p>
    As a director, my role was to ensure that the team had buy in, 
    the space to explore, a vetted direction, and the best path forward.
    My role was to de-risk our time-investment by ensuring that we were
    solving an important and impactful problem with the right solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Let's zoom into a root problem space one of the teams solved for,
    and how they solved it.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-focus">
    <header class="case-study-focus__header">
      <h3>
        Problem Space #1
      </h3>
    </header>

    <p>
      Customers aren't discovering value outside of file, sync and share.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>
    I love the double diamond.
    This is the foundation I lay for my teams, and for the team solving
    this problem.
    </strong>
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-double-diamond.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        An abstraction of the double diamond design thinking process made 
        popularized by the British Design Council.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    But at first, our problem was too big and we needed a short learning cycle.
    So, I pulled from another tool in my toolkit. The Google Venture Design
    Sprint, similar to the Double Diamond, emphasizes effective problem
    identification and iterative testing. It accelerates learning and provides
    clear direction. I guided a Designer and a Product Manager to leverage a
    Design Sprint. The experienced designer took charge, and the project kicked
    off with a team of 2 designers, 2 product managers, 1 data scientist, 1
    content designer, 1 researcher, and 2 engineers.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-design-sprint.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        An abstraction of the 5-day Design Sprint Process
        made famous by Jake Knapp. Created while Jake Knapp
        was at Google Ventures. This was used to demonstrate the
        similarities to design thinking and
        get alignment on using the process
        for vague problem spaces.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>
      On day one,
    </strong>
    the team, and leadership, had numerous assumptions to challenge:
    people struggle to find value due to a cluttered product, FSS (File, Sync
    and Share) is the only value, other features are neglected, and even if
    discovered our users lack knowledge on their usage. Leveraging initial
    assumptions, research and behavioral data, the team came away with a
    specific assumption they wanted to test. As the approver, I approved testing
    the assumption that relevant communication enhances feature and product
    discovery effectiveness.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>
      As the team diverged and converged,
    </strong>
    I had the privilege of participating in
    crazy-8s. One intriguing suggestion was a bot named
    "Friend Lee" on Dropbox, acting as a fake teammate who learns from your
    actions and guides you. Although deemed too unconventional, it remains an
    idea I love. By the end of the second day, they selected two solutions
    to test their assumption about relevance.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>
      On prototype day,
      the team commenced building
      their ideas in Figma.
    </strong>
    The skilled
    designers on the team crafted two relatively polished experiences for
    testing.
    One solution
    involved a quiz-based on-boarding process that transparently gathered
    insights from customers while reciprocating with valuable feedback. The
    other consisted of a pattern triggered by actions, leading to a workflow
    chain.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>
      Finally, we tested the solutions.
    </strong>
    The prototypes underwent testing with 12 customers within a single day. The
    two designers, in collaboration with the researchers, conducted
    two distinct tests.
    Each test involved six users.
    Active participation and
    note-taking was required from everyone involved.
    The outcome revealed that
    relevance played a pivotal role.
    Smart suggestions that followed actions
    proved to be effective, and customers were willing to share information if
    they understood it would guide them towards specific actions.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>
      The sprint was a success.
    </strong>
    The team had validated their assumption — “Feature
    and product discovery communication is effective when relevant.“ From here,
    we would start to plan a series of experiments based off of this learning.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>
      After the design sprint we explored fresh
      ways to communicate with our customers, discovered new opportunities to
    engage them, and found different ways to understand their needs.
    </strong>
    Post sprint,
    we conducted 12 experiments
    focused on connecting our customers to the full
    value of Dropbox.
    We have continued to iterate to with a combination of A/B tests
    and learning experiments.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-experiment-map.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        The series of experiments from 2022 to 2023 that landed us at the
        Q2, 2023 solution for connecting our users to the full
        value of Dropbox.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    The Design Sprint kicked off a series of experiments that
    have led us to a combination
    of general (weak behavioral knowledge of a customer)
    and targeted (strong behavioral knowledge of a customer)
    activation approach
    as opposed to a one-size fits all approach.
  </p>

  <p>
    Here is part of the solution we landed on. Dropbox is continuing to explore
    in the second quarter of 2023.
  </p>
