  <a name="challenges"></a>
  <h1>
    The Challenges
  </h1>

  <p>
    <strong>Different teams had goals that 
    incentivized them to simply get as much traffic as possible to show gains.
    </strong>
    This set up a lot of
    internal competition for our customer’s attention.
    To solve for this, I drafted an engagement model that
    focused on empowering experimentation, while holding a high quality bar for
    shipping something to a general audience.
    It specified criteria for exiting each stage, and most importantly,
    a process for escalation.
    My product partner Frances took this and ran with it. She instilled this
    process across our org.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-working-model.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        A view of the Dropbox Core Working Model that
        was created to improve outcomes
        through aligning incentives.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>We also struggled with a bad user experience.</strong>
    The varied ways teams went about getting traffic resulted in what was
    referred to as a “billboard” experience. Customers got peppered
    with upsells to different products, or blocking recommendations to new
    features. To solve for this I created the CCC framework. Customer, Context
    and Content focused on quality over quantity of users. We tasked 1 team to
    create an internal case study to prove the effectiveness of the CCC
    framework.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-focus">
    <header class="case-study-focus__header">
      <h3>
        The Case Study
      </h3>
    </header>

    <p>
      <strong>Experiment A</strong>: A page takeover in the form of a modal when
      a customer lands. The modal asked the user to "Try DropboxSign".  Of 10K
      people that saw it, 2.7% clicked, and 15 trials started. A 0.15% success.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Experiment B</strong>:
      A rich confirmation (content) appearing when
      a customer uploads a PDF (context)
      because we suspect they need signing capabilities based on the file name
      (customer). Of 2K people that saw it,
      5% clicked, 80 trials converted. 
      3.6% success. Roughly 300% better.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-bad-ux-before.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        Before: a page takeover often used to get clicks to drive
        users to a feature. It blocked users and was a very ineffective design.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-bad-ux-after.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        After: A "rich confirmation" popping up after a user takes an action.
        The confirmation is non-blocking, happens in response to an action, and
        guides the user to a connecting action.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    With teams collaborating, and guidance on design strategy,
    we tackled <strong>an inconsistent UI.</strong>
    There was no source
    of truth for how activation experiences should be designed,
    none the less,
    how the interfaces should look.
    This resulted in many disparate experiences and interfaces.
    I tasked a design manager to
    build out a component library and partnered with them to evangelize
    it.
  </p>

  <div class="case-study-image-container">
    <figure class="case-study-image">
      <%= image_tag "case_studies/dropbox-activation-inconsistent-ui.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        An abstraction of how the collection of components was presented. A
        name, a description, a visual of the component and information on how,
        and when, to use each component.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <a name="learnings"></a>
  <h1>
    Learnings
  </h1>

  <p>
    Our biggest learning was that 
    <strong>a one size fits all approach doesn't scale.</strong>
    As the offerings of a product grows, the audience becomes more complex,
    and their array of jobs-to-be-done expands.
    A combination of general activation (weak customer behavioral data)
    and targeted activation (strong customer behavioral data)
    is
    an effective way to scale an activation experience as a product grows.
  </p>

  <p>
    But shipping at scale is only effective if the org is set up
    to do so.
    We learned that
    <strong>
    goals drive outcomes more than principles.
    </strong>
    Misaligned goals can drive bad outcomes regardlress of intention.
    If goals are
    misaligned there is a high risk that one team’s work can negatively impact
    that of another’s.
  </p>

  <p>
    Finally,
    we learned that <strong>time constraints are our friends.</strong>
    When we forced time constraints, our rigor went up, our scope down. Speed
    became a valuable constraint to keep us from over investing in ideas that
    were not validated. This shaped
    <%= link_to raw("one of my leadership values: to encourage deadlines."), 
      values_path(anchor: 'encourage-deadlines') %>
  </p>

  <a name="closing"></a>
  <h1>
    Closing
  </h1>

  <p>
    Our journey to connect customers to the full value of Dropbox involved
    thorough research, collaboration, and iterative testing. We identified key
    problem areas and validated the importance of relevance in feature and
    product discovery. By developing a full funnel experience that leverages
    data models for relevant recommendations, we have achieved impactful
    results, increased engagement metrics, and validated a new activation
    direction. Overcoming challenges through inclusive planning, aligned goals,
    and streamlined processes, the team will continue refining their strategy to
    provide a seamless and valuable user experience.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thanks for reading.
    If you have any questions or comments, please don't hesitate
